1. Calculate the sum of squares of elements in both arrays using nested loops.
2. Calculate the minimum of the two sums to find the initial minimum sum of squared differences.
3. Iterate through the arrays again, checking if the absolute value of each element is less than or equal to k1 and k2 respectively.
4. Update the minimum sum of squared differences if a smaller sum is found.
5. Return the final minimum sum of squared differences.

This solution has a time complexity of O(n) because we iterate through the arrays once to calculate the initial sum of squared differences and another time to update the minimum sum if necessary. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a single integer variable to store the minimum sum of squared differences. The energy implications are low because no energy-consuming operations are performed.

